description.plain:
When a young cadet officer wrote to the poet Rainer Maria Rilke at the turn of the 20th century, seeking feedback on his verses, Rilke declined to give criticism. Instead, he counseled the young writer to turn inward and seek insight from the solitude of everyday life: “To walk inside yourself and meet no one for hours—that is what you must be able to attain.” The gentle, understated music of Los Angeles singer-songwriter Helen Ballentine, aka Skullcrusher, proves how generative this patient self-reflection can be. In 2018, after abandoning a career in visual arts, she entered a period of existential uncertainty, during which she tentatively decided to pursue music for the first time. Unemployment gave her the freedom to sit with herself. As a testament to the confidence she developed, Skullcrusher, her debut EP, is “an exploration of the ways you become yourself when you aren’t looking.”

Source: Cat Zhang @ Pitchfork https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/skullcrusher-placesplans/

body.plain:
When a young cadet officer wrote to the poet Rainer Maria Rilke at the turn of the 20th century, seeking feedback on his verses, Rilke declined to give criticism. Instead, he counseled the young writer to turn inward and seek insight from the solitude of everyday life: “To walk inside yourself and meet no one for hours—that is what you must be able to attain.” The gentle, understated music of Los Angeles singer-songwriter Helen Ballentine, aka Skullcrusher, proves how generative this patient self-reflection can be. In 2018, after abandoning a career in visual arts, she entered a period of existential uncertainty, during which she tentatively decided to pursue music for the first time. Unemployment gave her the freedom to sit with herself. As a testament to the confidence she developed, Skullcrusher, her debut EP, is “an exploration of the ways you become yourself when you aren’t looking.”

Source: Cat Zhang @ Pitchfork https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/skullcrusher-placesplans/

annotations:
Can I make it out there as I am?
 Without my name on a door or a headline band?

For musicians with some amount of attention or following, this line puts into focus what the whole verse is about: whether or not she can be liked or wanted for the kind of person she already is, not who she could become.

Do you think that I’m going places?
 Does it matter if I’m a really good friend?
 That I’m there when you call and when your shows end?

Like fellow folk singers Phoebe Bridgers or Julie Byrne, Ballentine wrings poignancy out of simple moments. Skullcrusher’s lead single, “Places/Plans” is a humble, lovely acoustic song about letting someone else in after a long period of being alone. “Do you think that I’m going places?” Ballentine sings with tender caution, her voice cottony and sweet. “Does it matter if I’m a really good friend/That I’m there when you call and when your shows end?” Light harmonies and spare guitar add to a feeling of unhurried tranquility. A new relationship could mean adjusting to someone else’s mode of being, but it could also mean letting them rest beside you in your solitude."

Source: Cat Zhang @ Pitchfork https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/skullcrusher-placesplans/

description.plain:
“Song for Nick Drake” is Skullcrusher’s first single release of 2021, which is about Skullcrusher’s relationship to the music of famed singer/songwriter Nick Drake.

She has also stated on an Instagram post that this single is “a song for walking alone.”
